node.text: During the long winter months, sometimes our camping gear takes its place in the storage closet until warmer weather returns in spring. But not so fast! Snow camping can be a unique, rewarding, and even comfortable experience, despite the colder temps. With the help of my friends at @eddiebauer, I’m sharing this quick how-to guide on snow camping. Check it out to ensure your first (or next) snow camp in your local snowy area is as enjoyable, safe, and memorable as any summer trip. #FindYourselfOutside #LiveYourAdventure

node.text:
Thrilled to share with you my new video reel, which includes some of the most special moments I’ve experienced in the outdoors and captured in motion. During a time when it’s crucial to appreciate the power and beauty of nature, even if just virtually, please take a minute and enjoy. The full version of this video is available on IGTV and on my YouTube channel, link in bio 🙏🏼
–
🎵: “Fear Not" by Ryan Taubert

node.text:
No better way to hit the reset button, ponder the universe, and connect under the same stars for one night, I’d say. My friends at @eddiebauer created this global holiday, #SleepUnderTheStars night, for that exact reason – and tonight is the night! If you plan to join, whether it’s by laying out a sleeping bag on your deck, hanging a hammock in the wilderness, or pitching a tent in the backyard, please enjoy to the fullest, be safe, and leave it better than you found it. I hope you will join me for #SleepUnderTheStars tonight, no matter where you are or how you experience it ✨ 
#eddiebauer #findyourselfoutside #ebcontributor

node.text: Simple scenes both big and small from a day beneath Tahoma (Mount Rainier). While I’d say there’s a time and place for well planned previsualized photography, to me sometimes the most refreshing thing is to just walk thru nature without expectation and to simply notice what I would otherwise miss.

node.text:
Pitch a tent in the yard, roll out a sleeping bag on your deck or balcony, or hang a hammock in the backcountry — however you can enjoy a night out under the stars. I can’t believe it’s just 10 days away – August 7th is the second #SleepUnderTheStars Night with my friends at @eddiebauer. Jill and I are currently weighing options – do we truck camp in @zeppthetruck, or should we do a little backpack trip? What do you think? For those joining, what are your plans? Let me know 👇 
@eddiebauer #findyourselfoutside #ebcontributor

node.text:
Exploring the depths of imagination and creativity in Utah’s canyons at night. I’m thrilled to share more of this new series of work I created with my friend @erinoutdoors. This conceptual project was beyond exciting: encountering what we could not see, introducing light & color to paint our environment, and letting our imaginations run wild with creative possibilities. The resulting images to me were surprising and unexpected in the best of ways. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Erin and I recently chatted about this unique collaboration with Sony Alpha Universe -- if interested, visit my profile link to check out our conversation -- and we discussed how the @sonyalpha a7S III, a low-light powerhouse, made this concept a reality. Many thanks to the talented @erinoutdoors for joining forces with me to create this series and to Sony for the amazing support.
@sonyalpha #alphacollective #bealpha

node.text:
“Desertluminescence”
This spring I spent a week in the Southwest creating a series of new images with my friend @erinoutdoors, in hopes of answering a question: what might we create with our low-light @sonyalpha gear and a mix of lighting (colored LEDs, flashlights, lanterns) inside Utah’s canyons at night? These deep, narrow spaces in the remote desert around the new moon would mean complete darkness, so we’d need to actively light our surroundings in order to see anything let alone create photographs.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Inspired by the night-related work of @itsreuben, @cathsimard, @dgilliver, and @ericparephoto, among others, we entered each canyon ready to experiment with various concepts of our own. But we knew our creative process would evolve in real time. Each night was a mix of trial and error but also breakthroughs that had us literally running around screaming with excitement! 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
This entire series, which @erinoutdoors and I jointly created as a unique collaboration, was created with Sony’s a7S III camera body and the new 14mm f/1.8 GM lens, among other lenses. We recently sat down with the Sony Alpha Universe team for a chat about this project - from concept to capture! You can check out our conversation in the link in my bio.
@sonyalpha #alphacollective #bealpha
#Desertluminescence

Pictured: 1) the neverending lake chelan under the cessna’s wing; 2) fractures in the Boston glacier, the largest in the park; 3) from Dakobed’s summit to Tahoma’s; 4) abstract patterns & textures near treeline; and 5) the north face of shuksan’s summit pyramid. Let me know your fav below ⬇️ !

node.text:
8 years ago when I moved from Minnesota to Seattle I never would have imagined the experiences I’d end up having in this mountain range. Nor would I have guessed the amount of outdoor gear I’d gather after getting into hiking, trail running, mountaineering, rock climbing, and more. Yes, I’ll admit I’m now a gear junkie, but I started off with more questions than answers, and I wish I had had more chances to test out gear early on and put it thru its paces. Well if you’re similarly just starting out or otherwise in need of gear, my friends at @eddiebauer just launched a new program that will allow you to get outdoors more affordably through a new gear rental service. If what you need is a tent, a pack, a sleeping bag, or whatnot, you can now rent some of the best gear out there, get it shipped right to your door, and be covered for whatever adventure you have your sights on. Check out the link in my profile (👉@scott_kranz) to learn more about this new program - and happy adventuring !
@eddiebauer #findyourselfoutside #ebcontributor

node.text: Let’s play a game. But first a quick story: another impromptu adventure happened this week when a forest road drive turned into a quick solo climb. Coming down the mountain after sunset, this scene stopped me in my tracks. So much to look at 🤯: vibrant sunset colors above a distant volcano, with a low marine layer covering the cascadian foothills, and a cloud waterfall to boot. I’ll be honest, the scene, although stunning, had almost too much to take in. So I did what I often do: seek out tighter visuals found within the wider frame. So, back to that game: If you could zoom into this wider view (on slide 1) and compose a tighter, more abstract shot, how would you frame it? What detail would you hone in on, and what what you include/exclude...or would you keep it wide? Let me know - what’s your shot?! And although there’s no right or wrong answer here (everyone sees and experiences their surroundings in their own way that’s true to them) I decided to share my “frames within the frame” on slides 2-5. Would love to hear from you ⬇️😊

node.text: With it being the last day in June, this news is belated, but I was thrilled to have my photo grace the cover of Backpacker Magazine again, this time for their May/June 2021 issue. It's always so rewarding to see your work in physical form, whether its an art print or an editorial piece such as this. And bottom line, I’m so damn thankful to do what I do for a living, so I’d say it’s important for me to pause from time to time and celebrate the wins, both big and small, that happen each and every day. And a shout out to my friends Pat and Kelly for letting me capture them enjoying a sunny day at one of Idaho's pristine alpine lakes - it *might* have been the case that that water was frigid, but they still relished the moment given the stunning scene we had all to ourselves✌️
